This project expects `wfkit` to be installed locally from `devDependencies`, so everyone on the team can run the same CLI version through package scripts.

## Start here

Update `wfkit.json` with your real Webflow and GitHub settings.

`deliveryMode` controls how production code gets back into Webflow:

- `cdn` publishes `dist/assets` to `assetBranch` and uses jsDelivr
- `inline` writes built module code back into Webflow as managed inline scripts

Keep your source code flow in normal feature branches and pull requests.

If you just ran `wfkit init` without `--skip-install`, dependencies are already installed.
After cloning the project later on another machine, install them with:

```bash
{{.InstallCommand}}
```

Then:

```bash
{{.RunScript}} dev
```

Open `http://localhost:3000` to work against your proxied `.webflow.io` site locally.

## Use the generated scripts

- `{{.RunScript}} dev` starts the Webflow proxy and local Vite dev server
- `{{.RunScript}} build` builds production assets into `dist/assets`
- `{{.RunScript}} docs` publishes `docs/index.md` to the `{{.DocsPageSlug}}` Webflow page
- `{{.RunScript}} publish` builds assets, publishes `dist/assets` to the configured asset branch, and updates Webflow production code
- `{{.RunScript}} lint` runs ESLint for scaffolded source files
- `{{.RunScript}} typecheck` runs TypeScript checks

## Understand the architecture

This scaffold separates _where code runs_ from _what code does_.

- `src/global/index.ts` is the one explicit global entry. Use it for behavior that should be available on every page.
- `src/global/modules/*` contains global modules that you choose to import from the global entry.
- `src/pages/*/index.ts` is for page-specific bootstrapping. A page file should decide what to mount on that page, not hold all the behavior itself.
- `src/features/*` is for reusable Webflow behavior. Put sliders, tabs, accordions, filters, toggles, and section logic here.
- `src/utils/dom.ts` contains low-level DOM helpers.
- `src/utils/webflow.ts` contains the Webflow-aware mounting helpers like `definePage`, `mountFeature`, and `onWebflowReady`.

The rule of thumb is:

- page files decide _where to mount_
- feature files define _what the behavior is_
- global files mount behavior shared across the whole site

## Use the project layout the intended way

```text
src/
  features/
    site-status.ts
  global/
    index.ts
    modules/
      site.global.ts
  pages/
    home/
      index.ts
  utils/
    dom.ts
    webflow.ts
build/
  webflow-vite-plugin.js
docs/
  index.md
dist/assets/
  wfkit-manifest.json
```

Use each area like this:

- `src/global/index.ts`: export your public helpers and mount shared site-wide modules
- `src/global/modules/*`: split shared global responsibilities into small modules
- `src/pages/home/index.ts`: keep page setup thin and focused on that page only
- `src/features/*`: build reusable behavior around stable `data-wf-*` selectors
- `build/webflow-vite-plugin.js`: controls how page and global entries become Webflow-ready bundles
- `docs/index.md`: the default docs hub entry

## Follow this workflow when adding code

1. Add the required `data-wf-*` attributes in Webflow so your code has stable mount points.
2. Put reusable behavior in `src/features/*`.
3. Mount that behavior from a page entry or a global module.
4. Use `{{.RunScript}} dev` to verify the behavior through the local proxy, not by editing Webflow production code directly.
5. When the behavior is ready, use `{{.RunScript}} publish`.

## Keep page files thin and DRY

Avoid writing all logic directly in `src/pages/*/index.ts`.
Instead, keep page files as orchestration and move real behavior into features.

Example:

```ts
// src/features/home-cta.ts
import { mountFeature } from "@/utils/webflow";

export function mountHomeCTA(root: ParentNode = document) {
  mountFeature(
    "home-cta",
    "[data-wf-home-cta]",
    (element) => {
      element.setAttribute("data-cta-ready", "true");
    },
    root,
  );
}
```

```ts
// src/pages/home/index.ts
import { definePage } from "@/utils/webflow";
import { mountHomeCTA } from "@/features/home-cta";

definePage("home", (pageRoot) => {
  mountHomeCTA(pageRoot);
});
```

This keeps selectors, DOM behavior, and reuse in one place.

## Decide where new code belongs

Use this quick guide:

- Put it in `src/features/*` if the same behavior could be reused on more than one page or section.
- Put it in `src/pages/*/index.ts` if the code is only about deciding what mounts on that page.
- Put it in `src/global/modules/*` if it should run site-wide.
- Put it in `src/utils/*` only if it is generic plumbing, not business behavior.

## Work with Webflow instead of against it

This scaffold is designed around Webflow's runtime:

- use stable `data-wf-*` attributes rather than brittle visual selectors
- prefer mounting behavior through `definePage` and `mountFeature`
- keep production updates behind `wfkit publish`, not manual script edits in Webflow
- treat Webflow as the source of markup and structure, and this codebase as the source of behavior
